amdgpu: gmc_v7_0 — also bind dummy page at GART VA 0 (v76d-β-2-A1.5)

v76d-β-2-A landed and made huge progress: the UVD VCPU firmware read
at GPU virtual 0x300000000 now succeeds, the fw is alive and executing
(MC client field shows UVD, not UMC), and the fault moved to a new
address: GPU virtual 0 (page 3145728 → page 0), with PROTECTIONS=0x0c
(read access on unmapped page) instead of 0x02 (PT walk failure).

Ghidra trace via the UVD IOCTL surface revealed that Sony lays out the
three UVD regions starting at GPU virtual 0x300000000 in vmid 4:
  - Region 1 (1920 KB firmware target) → 0x300000000..0x3001E0000
  - Region 2 (1168 KB heap/IB)         → 0x3001E0000..0x300304000
  - Region 3   (16 KB message queue)   → 0x300304000..0x300308000
  - First user-allocatable VA          → 0x300308000 (returned by ioctl 0x4008830c)

So when our dummy returns zeros at 0x300000000, the firmware probably
interprets those zeros as a pointer (e.g., "address of next config
struct") and dereferences it, hitting VA 0 → fault.

Cheapest test to verify the model: bind dummy at VA 0 too. The fw's
null-deref then resolves to the (zero-filled) dummy page instead of
faulting, and the fw progresses to whatever it reads NEXT — that next
fault address tells us about the firmware's state machine.

This patch adds one extra amdgpu_gart_bind(adev, 0, ...) call right
after the existing 0x300000000 bind from v76d-β-2-A. The TLB invalidate
moves to after the second bind so both PTEs are flushed together.

Risk: amdgpu's GART allocator may have claimed GART page 0 for an
early BO. Binding dummy there would overwrite that BO's PTE and could
regress GFX/SDMA/DCE. Watch dmesg for new probe-time errors and
compare with v76d-β-2-A (which booted clean).

Expected:
  ✅ The fault at VA 0 disappears, firmware progresses further.
     New fault elsewhere — tells us what the fw reads next.
  🟡 GFX/SDMA still work but firmware loops on the same VA 0
     (in our flat-walk model, GART[0] now returns zeros instead of
     faulting; if firmware re-dereferences 0 it'd infinite-loop on
     the dummy zeros).
  ❌ GFX/SDMA regress. Roll back to A1 not touching VA 0; pivot to
     A2 (allocate fresh GTT BO with non-trivial fw contents at
     0x300000000).

Build & USB-stage cleanly before submitting.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/gmc_v7_0.c
@@ -789,10 +789,32 @@
 		amdgpu_gart_bind(adev, 0x300000000ULL, 1, &fw_dummy,
 				 AMDGPU_PTE_VALID | AMDGPU_PTE_SYSTEM |
 				 AMDGPU_PTE_READABLE);
-		amdgpu_gart_invalidate_tlb(adev);
 		DRM_INFO("ps4: bound dummy page at GART virtual 0x300000000 "
 			 "(pa=0x%llx) for UVD fw access\n",
 			 (unsigned long long)fw_dummy);
+
+		/*
+		 * v76d-β-2-A1.5: chase the secondary firmware read.
+		 *
+		 * After bind at 0x300000000, the firmware succeeded the first
+		 * read (got zeros from dummy), interpreted zeros as a null
+		 * pointer, and faulted dereferencing GPU VA 0. Bind dummy at
+		 * VA 0 too so that dereference resolves instead of faulting.
+		 *
+		 * If amdgpu's GART allocator had already claimed GART page 0
+		 * for some other BO, this overwrite may cause a regression in
+		 * that subsystem (GFX, SDMA, or DCE). Watch for new errors
+		 * in their probe paths. If clean, the firmware moves to the
+		 * next access, and we learn more from the new fault.
+		 */
+		amdgpu_gart_bind(adev, 0x0ULL, 1, &fw_dummy,
+				 AMDGPU_PTE_VALID | AMDGPU_PTE_SYSTEM |
+				 AMDGPU_PTE_READABLE);
+		DRM_INFO("ps4: bound dummy page at GART virtual 0x0 "
+			 "(pa=0x%llx) for UVD fw null-deref\n",
+			 (unsigned long long)fw_dummy);
+
+		amdgpu_gart_invalidate_tlb(adev);
 	}

 	if (amdgpu_vm_fault_stop == AMDGPU_VM_FAULT_STOP_ALWAYS)
